<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,457,1058]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,415,457,482]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Diagnostic characters</emphasis>
. Thin turbiniform shell; relatively low spire; rounded aperture with reflexed inner lip; moderately wide and deep umbilicus; numerous fine and sinuous collabral threads crossed by weaker spiral ones; two peripheral lamellar keels bordering the anal slit. Protoconch: planispiral; 1.25 whorls; diameter about 150 µm; flocculent sculpture (granules aggregated in an irregular polygonal pattern); transition to the teleoconch preceded by a cord-like varix not extended to the whole peristome.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,457,1058]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,637,662]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Remarks</emphasis>
. The superficially similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Seguenza, 1880" authorityName="Seguenza" authorityYear="1880" box="[607,1057,637,662]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis box="[607,853,637,662]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Anatoma tenuisculpta</emphasis>
(Seguenza, 1880)
</taxonomicName>
is proportionally wider and more discoidal in shape. 
<taxonomicName box="[366,551,674,697]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[366,551,674,697]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Anatoma aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been often misidentified with 
<taxonomicName authority="Fleming, 1828" authorityName="Fleming" authorityYear="1828" box="[940,1253,673,698]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crispata">
<emphasis box="[940,1064,674,697]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">A. crispata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fleming" box="[1079,1245,673,698]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Fleming, J. (1828) A history of British animals, exhibiting the descriptive characters and systematical arrangement of genera and species of quadrupeds, birds, reptiles, fishes, mollusca, and radiata of the United Kingdom. Bell &amp; Bradfute, Edinburgh, J. Duncan, London, XXIII + 565 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 12859" type="book" year="1828">Fleming, 1828</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
that is probably absent in the Mediterranean, except for the Alboran basin (
<bibRefCitation author="Penas" box="[815,1014,709,734]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Penas, A., Rolan, E., Luque, A. A., Templado, J., Moreno, D., Rubio, F., Salas, C., Sierra, A. &amp; Gofas, S. (2006) Moluscos marinos de la isla de Alboran. Iberus, 24 (1), 23 - 151." type="journal article" year="2006">
Peñas 
<emphasis box="[890,947,709,734]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Micali" box="[1026,1280,709,734]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Micali, P. &amp; Geiger, D. L. (2015) Additions and corrections to the Scissurellidae and Anatomidae (Gastropoda-Vetigastropoda) of the Mediterranean Sea, with first record of Sinezona semicostata Burnay et Rolan, 1990. Biodiversity Journal, 6 (3), 703 - 708." type="journal article" year="2015">Micali &amp; Geiger 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The identity of Santa Maria di Leuca specimens was confirmed by Dr. D.L. Geiger, Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History (2016, personal communication). See 
<bibRefCitation author="Geiger" box="[577,735,781,806]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Geiger, D. L. (2012) Monograph of the little slit shells. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs, 7, 729 - 1291." type="journal article" year="2012">Geiger (2012)</bibRefCitation>
for a comprehensive chresonymy of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,457,1058]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,817,842]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Occurrence</emphasis>
. Box-corer samples BC05 (
<specimenCount box="[657,800,817,842]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="generic">3 specimens</specimenCount>
), BC66 (5), BC67 (1), BC70 (1), BC71 (3), BC72 (10); cores BC21 (1), BC51 (1), BC67 (1), BC72 (3). Maximum height: 
<quantity box="[901,990,853,878]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,457,1058]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,492,889,914]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[508,693,890,913]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[508,693,890,913]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Anatoma aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the Atlantic Ocean (from 
<collectingCountry box="[1107,1197,890,914]" name="Norway" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Norway</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1254,1405,889,914]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[151,236,925,950]" name="Angola" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Angola</collectingCountry>
, and possibly to the Caribbean) and in the Mediterranean as far East as the 
<collectingRegion box="[1084,1169,926,950]" country="Greece" name="Voreio Aigaio" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Aegean</collectingRegion>
Sea; it dwells on sandy to gravelly bottoms at shelf to bathyal depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Penas" box="[674,876,961,986]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Penas, A., Rolan, E., Luque, A. A., Templado, J., Moreno, D., Rubio, F., Salas, C., Sierra, A. &amp; Gofas, S. (2006) Moluscos marinos de la isla de Alboran. Iberus, 24 (1), 23 - 151." type="journal article" year="2006">
Peñas 
<emphasis box="[750,808,961,986]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoisaeter" box="[889,1058,961,986]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Hoisaeter, T. (2009) Distribution of marine, benthic, shell bearing gastropods along the Norwegian coast. Fauna norvegica, 28, 5 - 106." type="journal article" year="2009">Høisaeter 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Geiger" box="[1072,1216,961,986]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Geiger, D. L. (2012) Monograph of the little slit shells. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs, 7, 729 - 1291." type="journal article" year="2012">Geiger 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gofas" box="[1230,1431,961,986]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Gofas, S. &amp; Bouchet, P. (2014) Kelliella abyssicola (Forbes, 1844). In: MolluscaBase (2016). [World Register of Marine Species] Avaliable from: http: // www. marinespecies. org / aphia. php? p = taxdetails &amp; id = 140158 (Accessed 30 Aug. 2016)" type="book chapter" year="2014">
Gofas 
<emphasis box="[1305,1364,961,986]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cordeiro" box="[151,381,997,1022]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Cordeiro, R., Borges, J. P., Martins, A. M. F. &amp; Avila, S. P. (2015) Checklist of the littoral gastropods (Mollusca Gastropoda) from the Archipelago of the Azores (NE Atlantic). Biodiversity Journal, 6 (4), 855 - 900." type="journal article" year="2015">
Cordeiro 
<emphasis box="[257,314,997,1022]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
